{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775874957853,"sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","part":{"id":"prt_d7a654e0d0015A2Dnd7BG67V1H","messageID":"msg_d7a653c96001g9I7cTwtvtLvJr","sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-015/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-015/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-015: PicoD 命令执行 API - Delta Specification\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-015  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: **Base Spec:** [deployment/client-go.md](../../deployment/client-go.md)\n10: \n11: The PicoD Command Execution API provides a high-level interface for executing commands in sandbox environments. It supports both synchronous and asynchronous execution, with features including resource limits, output streaming, execution cancellation, and persistent status tracking.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: CommandExecutor Interface\n18: \n19: The system SHALL provide a `CommandExecutor` interface that supports synchronous execution, asynchronous execution, status retrieval, cancellation, and output streaming.\n20: \n21: #### Scenario: Execute runs command synchronously\n22: - **GIVEN** a valid `CommandExecutor` instance\n23: - **AND** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"echo\"`, `Args=[\"hello\"]`\n24: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n25: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL validate the request\n26: - **AND** execute the command in the sandbox\n27: - **AND** capture stdout and stderr\n28: - **AND** return an `ExecutionResult` with `ExitCode=0`, `Stdout=[]byte(\"hello\\n\")`\n29: - **AND** return `nil` error on successful execution\n30: \n31: #### Scenario: Execute returns error on invalid request\n32: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with empty `Command=\"\"`\n33: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n34: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n35: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating command is required\n36: - **AND** SHALL NOT attempt sandbox execution\n37: \n38: #### Scenario: Execute returns error on timeout\n39: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"sleep\"`, `Args=[\"60\"]`, `Timeout=1s`\n40: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n41: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n42: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL start the command\n43: - **AND** when timeout expires, cancel the execution\n44: - **AND** return an error indicating timeout occurred\n45: - **AND** the result SHALL have `Status.State=StateFailed`\n46: \n47: #### Scenario: ExecuteAsync queues command for background execution\n48: - **GIVEN** a valid `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"long-running-task\"`\n49: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n50: - **WHEN** `ExecuteAsync(ctx, req)` is called\n51: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL generate a unique `ExecutionID`\n52: - **AND** persist initial status with `State=StatePending`\n53: - **AND** queue the execution for background processing\n54: - **AND** return the `ExecutionID` immediately\n55: - **AND** return `nil` error\n56: \n57: #### Scenario: ExecuteAsync validates request before queuing\n58: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `WorkingDir=\"/nonexistent/path\"`\n59: - **AND** the working directory does not exist in sandbox\n60: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n61: - **WHEN** `ExecuteAsync(ctx, req)` is called\n62: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL validate the request\n63: - **AND** return an error indicating working directory is invalid\n64: - **AND** SHALL NOT queue the execution\n65: \n66: #### Scenario: GetStatus returns current execution status\n67: - **GIVEN** an execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-abc123\"` exists with `State=StateRunning`\n68: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n69: - **WHEN** `GetStatus(ctx, \"exec-abc123\")` is called\n70: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL query the status store\n71: - **AND** return an `ExecutionStatus` with `State=StateRunning`\n72: - **AND** return `nil` error\n73: \n74: #### Scenario: GetStatus returns completed status\n75: - **GIVEN** an execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-completed\"` has finished with exit code 0\n76: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n77: - **WHEN** `GetStatus(ctx, \"exec-completed\")` is called\n78: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ExecutionStatus` with:\n79:   - `State=StateCompleted`\n80:   - `ExitCode=*0` (pointer to 0)\n81:   - `FinishedAt` set to completion time\n82: - **AND** return `nil` error\n83: \n84: #### Scenario: GetStatus returns error for non-existent execution\n85: - **GIVEN** no execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-nonexistent\"` exists\n86: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n87: - **WHEN** `GetStatus(ctx, \"exec-nonexistent\")` is called\n88: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrExecutionNotFound`\n89: \n90: #### Scenario: Cancel stops a running execution\n91: - **GIVEN** an execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-running\"` with `State=StateRunning`\n92: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n93: - **WHEN** `Cancel(ctx, \"exec-running\")` is called\n94: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL signal the sandbox to terminate the process\n95: - **AND** update status to `State=StateCancelled`\n96: - **AND** return `nil` error\n97: \n98: #### Scenario: Cancel returns error for already completed execution\n99: - **GIVEN** an execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-done\"` with `State=StateCompleted`\n100: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n101: - **WHEN** `Cancel(ctx, \"exec-done\")` is called\n102: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrExecutionAlreadyComplete`\n103: \n104: #### Scenario: StreamOutput returns output channel for running execution\n105: - **GIVEN** an execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-streaming\"` with `State=StateRunning`\n106: - **AND** the execution is producing output\n107: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n108: - **WHEN** `StreamOutput(ctx, \"exec-streaming\")` is called\n109: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return a `<-chan OutputChunk` channel\n110: - **AND** the channel SHALL receive chunks as output is produced\n111: - **AND** the channel SHALL be closed when execution completes\n112: \n113: #### Scenario: StreamOutput returns error for non-existent execution\n114: - **GIVEN** no execution with `ExecutionID=\"exec-missing\"` exists\n115: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n116: - **WHEN** `StreamOutput(ctx, \"exec-missing\")` is called\n117: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrExecutionNotFound`\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ### Requirement: ExecutionRequest Validation\n122: \n123: The system SHALL validate `ExecutionRequest` fields and reject invalid configurations before execution.\n124: \n125: #### Scenario: Empty command is rejected\n126: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"\"`\n127: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n128: - **WHEN** any execution method is called with this request\n129: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return error `ErrInvalidCommand: command is required`\n130: \n131: #### Scenario: Command with path traversal is rejected\n132: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"../../../etc/passwd\"`\n133: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n134: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n135: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return error indicating command contains invalid characters\n136: \n137: #### Scenario: WorkingDir outside allowed paths is rejected\n138: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `WorkingDir=\"/etc\"`\n139: - **AND** allowed working directories are restricted to `/workspace/*`\n140: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n141: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n142: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return error `ErrInvalidWorkingDir: working directory not allowed`\n143: \n144: #### Scenario: Environment variable names are validated\n145: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Environment={\"INVALID-NAME\": \"value\"}`\n146: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n147: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n148: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return error indicating invalid environment variable name\n149: \n150: #### Scenario: SessionID is required for sandbox resolution\n151: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `SessionID=\"\"`\n152: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n153: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n154: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return error `ErrInvalidSessionID: session ID is required`\n155: \n156: ---\n157: \n158: ### Requirement: Resource Constraints Enforcement\n159: \n160: The system SHALL enforce resource limits on command executions through sandbox integration.\n161: \n162: #### Scenario: Memory limit is enforced\n163: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `ResourceLimits.MaxMemory=104857600` (100MB)\n164: - **AND** the command attempts to allocate 200MB\n165: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n166: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n167: - **THEN** the sandbox SHALL enforce the memory limit\n168: - **AND** the execution SHALL be terminated with `ExitCode != 0`\n169: - **AND** the result SHALL have `Error.Code=\"RESOURCE_EXCEEDED\"`\n170: \n171: #### Scenario: CPU limit is enforced\n172: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `ResourceLimits.MaxCPU=50.0` (50%)\n173: - **AND** the command is CPU-intensive\n174: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n175: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n176: - **THEN** the sandbox SHALL throttle CPU usage to 50%\n177: - **AND** execution SHALL complete within timeout\n178: \n179: #### Scenario: File descriptor limit is enforced\n180: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `ResourceLimits.MaxFiles=10`\n181: - **AND** the command attempts to open 20 files\n182: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n183: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n184: - **THEN** the sandbox SHALL return error on file open exceeding limit\n185: - **AND** `Error.Code=\"RESOURCE_EXCEEDED\"` with details about file limit\n186: \n187: #### Scenario: IO bandwidth limit is enforced\n188: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `ResourceLimits.MaxIOBytes=1048576` (1MB/s)\n189: - **AND** the command performs heavy IO operations\n190: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n191: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n192: - **THEN** the sandbox SHALL throttle IO to 1MB/s\n193: \n194: ---\n195: \n196: ### Requirement: Execution Status Management\n197: \n198: The system SHALL maintain execution status through state transitions and persist status in the store.\n199: \n200: #### Scenario: Status transitions from pending to running\n201: - **GIVEN** an async execution is queued with `State=StatePending`\n202: - **WHEN** the background worker picks up the execution\n203: - **THEN** the status SHALL be updated to `State=StateRunning`\n204: - **AND** `StartedAt` SHALL be set to current time\n205: \n206: #### Scenario: Status transitions from running to completed\n207: - **GIVEN** an execution with `State=StateRunning`\n208: - **AND** the command completes with exit code 0\n209: - **WHEN** the execution finishes\n210: - **THEN** the status SHALL be updated to `State=StateCompleted`\n211: - **AND** `ExitCode` SHALL be set to 0\n212: - **AND** `FinishedAt` SHALL be set to current time\n213: \n214: #### Scenario: Status transitions from running to failed\n215: - **GIVEN** an execution with `State=StateRunning`\n216: - **AND** the command exits with non-zero code\n217: - **WHEN** the execution finishes\n218: - **THEN** the status SHALL be updated to `State=StateFailed`\n219: - **AND** `ExitCode` SHALL be set to the actual exit code\n220: - **AND** `FinishedAt` SHALL be set to current time\n221: - **AND** `Error` SHALL contain failure details\n222: \n223: #### Scenario: Status transitions to cancelled\n224: - **GIVEN** an execution with `State=StateRunning`\n225: - **WHEN** `Cancel()` is called\n226: - **THEN** the status SHALL be updated to `State=StateCancelled`\n227: - **AND** `FinishedAt` SHALL be set to cancellation time\n228: - **AND** `ExitCode` SHALL be nil or reflect termination signal\n229: \n230: #### Scenario: Terminal states are immutable\n231: - **GIVEN** an execution with `State=StateCompleted`\n232: - **WHEN** any status update is attempted\n233: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL reject the update\n234: - **AND** return error indicating execution is in terminal state\n235: \n236: ---\n237: \n238: ### Requirement: Output Capture and Streaming\n239: \n240: The system SHALL capture command output (stdout/stderr) and support real-time streaming.\n241: \n242: #### Scenario: Output is captured for sync execution\n243: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Command=\"echo\"`, `Args=[\"stdout\"]`, stdout redirected\n244: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n245: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n246: - **THEN** the `ExecutionResult.Stdout` SHALL contain `[]byte(\"stdout\\n\")`\n247: \n248: #### Scenario: Stderr is captured separately\n249: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` that writes to stderr\n250: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n251: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n252: - **THEN** the `ExecutionResult.Stderr` SHALL contain the error output\n253: - **AND** `ExecutionResult.Stdout` SHALL be empty or contain stdout only\n254: \n255: #### Scenario: Output size limit is enforced\n256: - **GIVEN** configuration `max_output_size=1MB`\n257: - **AND** a command that produces 10MB of output\n258: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n259: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n260: - **THEN** output capture SHALL be truncated at 1MB\n261: - **AND** `ExecutionResult` SHALL indicate truncation occurred\n262: \n263: #### Scenario: StreamOutput delivers chunks in order\n264: - **GIVEN** an async execution is running and producing output\n265: - **AND** a client calls `StreamOutput(ctx, id)`\n266: - **WHEN** the command writes \"line1\\nline2\\n\"\n267: - **THEN** the channel SHALL receive `OutputChunk{Data: []byte(\"line1\\n\"), Type: Stdout}`\n268: - **AND** then `OutputChunk{Data: []byte(\"line2\\n\"), Type: Stdout}`\n269: - **AND** chunks SHALL be in order of production\n270: \n271: #### Scenario: StreamOutput context cancellation stops streaming\n272: - **GIVEN** a client is streaming output from an execution\n273: - **AND** the client cancels the context\n274: - **WHEN** the context cancellation is detected\n275: - **THEN** the output channel SHALL be closed\n276: - **AND** the streaming goroutine SHALL exit cleanly\n277: \n278: #### Scenario: Output buffering respects buffer size limits\n279: - **GIVEN** configuration `output_buffer_size=4KB`\n280: - **AND** a command producing continuous output\n281: - **WHEN** output exceeds 4KB\n282: - **THEN** older output SHALL be discarded or flushed to store\n283: - **AND** buffer SHALL not exceed configured size\n284: \n285: ---\n286: \n287: ### Requirement: Error Handling and Error Types\n288: \n289: The system SHALL define and return appropriate error types for different failure scenarios.\n290: \n291: #### Scenario: ErrInvalidRequest for malformed requests\n292: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with invalid fields\n293: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n294: - **THEN** the error SHALL be `ErrInvalidRequest`\n295: - **AND** the error message SHALL describe which field is invalid\n296: \n297: #### Scenario: ErrResourceExceeded for resource limit violations\n298: - **GIVEN** an execution that exceeds memory limits\n299: - **WHEN** the sandbox terminates the process\n300: - **THEN** the result SHALL contain `Error` with `Code=\"RESOURCE_EXCEEDED\"`\n301: - **AND** `Error.Message` SHALL indicate which resource was exceeded\n302: \n303: #### Scenario: ErrTimeout for execution timeout\n304: - **GIVEN** an execution with `Timeout=5s`\n305: - **AND** the command runs longer than 5 seconds\n306: - **WHEN** timeout occurs\n307: - **THEN** the error SHALL be `ErrTimeout`\n308: - **AND** `ExecutionStatus.State` SHALL be `StateFailed`\n309: \n310: #### Scenario: ErrSandboxUnavailable when sandbox is not accessible\n311: - **GIVEN** a `SessionID` that resolves to an unreachable sandbox\n312: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n313: - **THEN** the error SHALL be `ErrSandboxUnavailable`\n314: - **AND** the error SHALL include sandbox identification details\n315: \n316: #### Scenario: ErrExecutionFailed for non-zero exit codes\n317: - **GIVEN** a command that exits with code 1\n318: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` completes\n319: - **THEN** the result SHALL have `ExitCode=1`\n320: - **AND** the error SHALL be `ErrExecutionFailed` with exit code in details\n321: \n322: #### Scenario: ErrCancelled for cancelled executions\n323: - **GIVEN** a running execution\n324: - **WHEN** `Cancel(ctx, id)` is called\n325: - **THEN** the status SHALL be `StateCancelled`\n326: - **AND** subsequent calls to `GetStatus` SHALL indicate cancellation\n327: \n328: ---\n329: \n330: ### Requirement: Integration with Sandbox Interface\n331: \n332: The system SHALL integrate with the sandbox interface (AR-009) for actual command execution.\n333: \n334: #### Scenario: Sandbox is resolved by SessionID\n335: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `SessionID=\"sess-abc123\"`\n336: - **AND** session `\"sess-abc123\"` exists in the store with sandbox info\n337: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n338: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n339: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL query the store for sandbox info\n340: - **AND** resolve the sandbox endpoint from `SandboxInfo.EntryPoints`\n341: \n342: #### Scenario: Sandbox connection failures are handled\n343: - **GIVEN** a valid `SessionID` pointing to a sandbox\n344: - **AND** the sandbox pod is not responding\n345: - **AND** a `CommandExecutor` instance\n346: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n347: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `ErrSandboxUnavailable`\n348: - **AND** the error SHALL include the connection failure reason\n349: \n350: #### Scenario: Sandbox environment variables are merged\n351: - **GIVEN** an `ExecutionRequest` with `Environment={\"FOO\": \"bar\"}`\n352: - **AND** the sandbox has default environment variables\n353: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n354: - **THEN** the request environment SHALL override sandbox defaults\n355: - **AND** merged environment SHALL be passed to the sandbox\n356: \n357: ---\n358: \n359: ### Requirement: Integration with Status Store\n360: \n361: The system SHALL persist execution status and metadata using the store interface (AR-012/AR-013/AR-014).\n362: \n363: #### Scenario: Execution status is persisted on state change\n364: - **GIVEN** an async execution transitions from `StatePending` to `StateRunning`\n365: - **WHEN** the state change occurs\n366: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL call `store.UpdateStatus(ctx, status)`\n367: - **AND** the update SHALL succeed before acknowledging the transition\n368: \n369: #### Scenario: Store failures are handled gracefully\n370: - **GIVEN** an execution completes successfully\n371: - **AND** the store is temporarily unavailable\n372: - **WHEN** status update is attempted\n373: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL log the error\n374: - **AND** return the execution result to the caller\n375: - **AND** status MAY be inconsistent (documented limitation)\n376: \n377: #### Scenario: Output is stored for later retrieval\n378: - **GIVEN** a completed execution with captured output\n379: - **WHEN** the execution finishes\n380: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL store output in the store\n381: - **AND** subsequent `GetStatus` calls SHALL include output reference\n382: \n383: ---\n384: \n385: ### Requirement: ExecutionID Generation\n386: \n387: The system SHALL generate unique execution identifiers for tracking.\n388: \n389: #### Scenario: ExecutionID is unique per execution\n390: - **GIVEN** multiple `ExecuteAsync` calls\n391: - **WHEN** each call returns an `ExecutionID`\n392: - **THEN** all returned IDs SHALL be unique\n393: - **AND** no two executions SHALL share the same ID\n394: \n395: #### Scenario: ExecutionID format is valid\n396: - **GIVEN** an execution is queued\n397: - **WHEN** `ExecuteAsync` returns\n398: - **THEN** the `ExecutionID` SHALL match pattern `^[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+$`\n399: - **AND** length SHALL be between 8 and 64 characters\n400: \n401: ---\n402: \n403: ### Requirement: Context Cancellation Handling\n404: \n405: The system SHALL respect context cancellation and clean up resources appropriately.\n406: \n407: #### Scenario: Execute cancels on context cancellation\n408: - **GIVEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is running\n409: - **AND** the context is cancelled\n410: - **WHEN** cancellation is detected\n411: - **THEN** the execution SHALL be terminated\n412: - **AND** error `ErrCancelled` SHALL be returned\n413: \n414: #### Scenario: GetStatus returns error on cancelled context\n415: - **GIVEN** a cancelled context\n416: - **WHEN** `GetStatus(ctx, id)` is called\n417: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return the context error\n418: - **AND** SHALL NOT query the store\n419: \n420: #### Scenario: Cleanup on context cancellation\n421: - **GIVEN** an async execution is streaming output\n422: - **AND** the context is cancelled\n423: - **WHEN** cancellation propagates\n424: - **THEN** all goroutines SHALL exit\n425: - **AND** channels SHALL be closed\n426: - **AND** no goroutine leaks SHALL occur\n427: \n428: ---\n429: \n430: ### Requirement: Concurrent Execution Limits\n431: \n432: The system SHALL enforce limits on concurrent command executions.\n433: \n434: #### Scenario: Concurrent limit is enforced\n435: - **GIVEN** configuration `max_concurrent_executions=10`\n436: - **AND** 10 executions are currently running\n437: - **WHEN** an 11th execution is requested\n438: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL queue the request\n439: - **OR** return `ErrTooManyConcurrentExecutions`\n440: \n441: #### Scenario: Queued execution starts when slot available\n442: - **GIVEN** `max_concurrent_executions=5`\n443: - **AND** 5 executions are running\n444: - **AND** 3 executions are queued\n445: - **WHEN** one running execution completes\n446: - **THEN** the first queued execution SHALL start\n447: - **AND** its status SHALL transition to `StateRunning`\n448: \n449: ---\n450: \n451: ### Requirement: Configuration\n452: \n453: The system SHALL read PicoD configuration from environment variables.\n454: \n455: #### Scenario: Default timeout is applied\n456: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT=30s`\n457: - **AND** an `ExecutionRequest` with no `Timeout` set\n458: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n459: - **THEN** the default timeout of 30s SHALL be applied\n460: \n461: #### Scenario: Max output size is configurable\n462: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE=5MB`\n463: - **AND** a command producing large output\n464: - **WHEN** `Execute(ctx, req)` is called\n465: - **THEN** output SHALL be limited to 5MB\n466: \n467: #### Scenario: Max concurrent executions is configurable\n468: - **GIVEN** environment `PICOD_MAX_CONCURRENT=50`\n469: - **WHEN** the `CommandExecutor` is initialized\n470: - **THEN** the concurrent execution limit SHALL be set to 50\n471: \n472: ---\n473: \n474: ## Changes to Base Specification\n475: \n476: No modifications to existing interfaces. This AR introduces new functionality in the `pkg/picod` module.\n477: \n478: ---\n479: \n480: ## New Interfaces\n481: \n482: ### CommandExecutor Interface\n483: \n484: ```go\n485: package picod\n486: \n487: import \"context\"\n488: \n489: // CommandExecutor defines the interface for executing commands in sandboxes.\n490: type CommandExecutor interface {\n491:     // Execute runs a command synchronously and returns the result.\n492:     Execute(ctx context.Context, req ExecutionRequest) (*ExecutionResult, error)\n493:     \n494:     // ExecuteAsync runs a command asynchronously and returns an execution ID.\n495:     ExecuteAsync(ctx context.Context, req ExecutionRequest) (ExecutionID, error)\n496:     \n497:     // GetStatus retrieves the current status of an execution.\n498:     GetStatus(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (*ExecutionStatus, error)\n499:     \n500:     // Cancel stops a running execution.\n501:     Cancel(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) error\n502:     \n503:     // StreamOutput returns a channel for streaming output from an execution.\n504:     StreamOutput(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (<-chan OutputChunk, error)\n505: }\n506: ```\n507: \n508: ### Execution Types\n509: \n510: ```go\n511: // ExecutionID uniquely identifies a command execution.\n512: type ExecutionID string\n513: \n514: // ExecutionRequest contains parameters for command execution.\n515: type ExecutionRequest struct {\n516:     Command        string\n517:     Args           []string\n518:     WorkingDir     string\n519:     Environment    map[string]string\n520:     Timeout        time.Duration\n521:     ResourceLimits ResourceConstraints\n522:     SessionID      string\n523: }\n524: \n525: // ExecutionResult contains the result of a command execution.\n526: type ExecutionResult struct {\n527:     ID         ExecutionID\n528:     Status     ExecutionStatus\n529:     ExitCode   int\n530:     Stdout     []byte\n531:     Stderr     []byte\n532:     StartedAt  time.Time\n533:     FinishedAt time.Time\n534:     Error      *ExecutionError\n535: }\n536: \n537: // ExecutionStatus represents the current state of an execution.\n538: type ExecutionStatus struct {\n539:     ID         ExecutionID\n540:     State      ExecutionState\n541:     StartedAt  *time.Time\n542:     FinishedAt *time.Time\n543:     ExitCode   *int\n544: }\n545: \n546: // ExecutionState represents the state of command execution.\n547: type ExecutionState string\n548: \n549: const (\n550:     StatePending   ExecutionState = \"pending\"\n551:     StateRunning   ExecutionState = \"running\"\n552:     StateCompleted ExecutionState = \"completed\"\n553:     StateFailed    ExecutionState = \"failed\"\n554:     StateCancelled ExecutionState = \"cancelled\"\n555: )\n556: \n557: // ResourceConstraints defines resource limits for execution.\n558: type ResourceConstraints struct {\n559:     MaxMemory  int64   // bytes\n560:     MaxCPU     float64 // percentage (0-100)\n561:     MaxIOBytes int64   // bytes per second\n562:     MaxFiles   int     // max open file descriptors\n563: }\n564: \n565: // ExecutionError contains detailed error information.\n566: type ExecutionError struct {\n567:     Code    string\n568:     Message string\n569:     Details map[string]interface{}\n570: }\n571: \n572: // OutputChunk represents a piece of output from a command.\n573: type OutputChunk struct {\n574:     Data      []byte\n575:     Type      OutputType\n576:     Timestamp time.Time\n577: }\n578: \n579: // OutputType indicates the source of output.\n580: type OutputType string\n581: \n582: const (\n583:     Stdout OutputType = \"stdout\"\n584:     Stderr OutputType = \"stderr\"\n585: )\n586: \n587: // ExecutorOptions contains configuration for CommandExecutor.\n588: type ExecutorOptions struct {\n589:     DefaultTimeout         time.Duration\n590:     MaxConcurrentExecutions int\n591:     MaxOutputSize          int64\n592:     OutputBufferSize       int\n593: }\n594: ```\n595: \n596: ### Error Types\n597: \n598: ```go\n599: var (\n600:     ErrInvalidRequest               = errors.New(\"picod: invalid request\")\n601:     ErrInvalidCommand               = errors.New(\"picod: command is required\")\n602:     ErrInvalidSessionID             = errors.New(\"picod: session ID is required\")\n603:     ErrInvalidWorkingDir            = errors.New(\"picod: invalid working directory\")\n604:     ErrResourceExceeded             = errors.New(\"picod: resource limits exceeded\")\n605:     ErrTimeout                      = errors.New(\"picod: execution timeout\")\n606:     ErrSandboxUnavailable           = errors.New(\"picod: sandbox unavailable\")\n607:     ErrExecutionFailed              = errors.New(\"picod: execution failed\")\n608:     ErrExecutionNotFound            = errors.New(\"picod: execution not found\")\n609:     ErrExecutionAlreadyComplete     = errors.New(\"picod: execution already complete\")\n610:     ErrTooManyConcurrentExecutions  = errors.New(\"picod: too many concurrent executions\")\n611:     ErrCancelled                    = errors.New(\"picod: execution cancelled\")\n612: )\n613: ```\n614: \n615: ---\n616: \n617: ## Modified Interfaces\n618: \n619: None. This AR introduces new functionality without modifying existing interfaces.\n620: \n621: ---\n622: \n623: ## Behavioral Changes\n624: \n625: | Behavior | Before | After |\n626: |----------|--------|-------|\n627: | Command execution | Direct sandbox calls | Through PicoD API with resource limits |\n628: | Execution tracking | No persistence | Persistent status in store |\n629: | Output handling | Direct capture | Buffered, size-limited capture |\n630: | Cancellation | Not supported | Supported via Cancel() API |\n631: | Streaming | Not supported | Real-time output streaming |\n632: \n633: ---\n634: \n635: ## Dependencies\n636: \n637: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n638: |------------|---------|---------|\n639: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/sandbox` | Local | Sandbox interface (AR-009) |\n640: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/store` | Local | Status persistence (AR-012/AR-013/AR-014) |\n641: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | Local | Shared types |\n642: | `github.com/google/uuid` | v1.x | ExecutionID generation |\n643: \n644: ---\n645: \n646: ## File Index\n647: \n648: | Path | Purpose |\n649: |------|---------|\n650: | `pkg/picod/executor.go` | CommandExecutor implementation |\n651: | `pkg/picod/executor_test.go` | Unit tests |\n652: | `pkg/picod/types.go` | Request/response type definitions |\n653: | `pkg/picod/status.go` | Execution status management |\n654: | `pkg/picod/output.go` | Output capture and streaming |\n655: | `pkg/picod/errors.go` | Error type definitions |\n656: | `pkg/picod/validation.go` | Request validation logic |\n657: \n658: ---\n659: \n660: ## Constants\n661: \n662: | Constant | Value | Description |\n663: |----------|-------|-------------|\n664: | `defaultTimeout` | `30s` | Default execution timeout |\n665: | `maxConcurrentDefault` | `100` | Default concurrent execution limit |\n666: | `maxOutputSizeDefault` | `10MB` | Default max output capture size |\n667: | `outputBufferSizeDefault` | `4KB` | Default output buffer size |\n668: | `executionIDLength` | `16` | Length of generated execution IDs |\n669: \n670: ---\n671: \n672: ## Configuration\n673: \n674: ### Environment Variables\n675: \n676: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n677: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n678: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default timeout for command execution |\n679: | `PICOD_MAX_CONCURRENT` | No | `100` | Maximum concurrent executions |\n680: | `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE` | No | `10MB` | Maximum output capture size |\n681: | `PICOD_OUTPUT_BUFFER_SIZE` | No | `4KB` | Output buffer size for streaming |\n682: \n683: ---\n684: \n685: ## API Endpoints Summary\n686: \n687: This AR provides library functionality; no HTTP endpoints are directly exposed.\n688: \n689: | Consumer | Usage |\n690: |----------|-------|\n691: | Workload Manager | Execute commands in sandboxes |\n692: | CLI Toolkit | Synchronous command execution |\n693: | Integration Layer | Async execution with streaming |\n694: \n695: ---\n696: \n697: ## Migration Notes\n698: \n699: - **New dependencies**: Add `github.com/google/uuid` to go.mod\n700: - **Store dependency**: Requires working store (Redis/Valkey) for status persistence\n701: - **Sandbox dependency**: Requires functional sandbox interface (AR-009)\n702: - **No breaking changes**: PicoD API is additive layer on existing components\n703: \n704: ---\n705: \n706: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n707: \n708: 1. **Interface Completeness**: All CommandExecutor methods implemented\n709: 2. **Request Validation**: Invalid requests rejected before execution\n710: 3. **Resource Enforcement**: Resource limits enforced via sandbox integration\n711: 4. **Status Tracking**: State transitions persisted correctly\n712: 5. **Output Handling**: Stdout/stderr captured and streamable\n713: 6. **Cancellation**: Running executions can be cancelled\n714: 7. **Error Types**: Appropriate errors returned for each failure mode\n715: 8. **Context Handling**: Respects context cancellation\n716: 9. **Concurrency Limits**: Enforced and queued correctly\n717: 10. **Integration**: Works with sandbox (AR-009) and store (AR-012/AR-013/AR-014)\n\n(End of file - total 717 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-015: PicoD 命令执行 API - Delta Specification\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-015  \n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Base Spec:** [deployment/client-go.md](../../deployment/client-go.md)\n\nThe PicoD Command Execution API provides a high-level interface for executing commands in sandbox environments. It supports both synchronous and asynchronous execution, with features including resource limits, output streaming, execution cancellation, and persistent status tracking.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: CommandExecutor Interface\n\nThe system SHALL provide a `CommandExecutor` interface that supports synchronous execution, asynchronous execution, status retrieval, cancellation, and output streaming.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-015/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775874957830,"end":1775874957851}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775874957856,"sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","part":{"id":"prt_d7a655514001Vqo2MHeYJE9KL4","messageID":"msg_d7a653c96001g9I7cTwtvtLvJr","sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-013/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-013/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-013: Redis 存储实现 (Redis Storage Implementation) - Delta Specification\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-013  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/store`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: **Base Spec:** [AR-012: 会话存储接口定义](../AR-012/delta-spec.md)\n10: \n11: The Redis Storage Implementation provides concrete implementations of the Store interface using Redis and Valkey as backends. It handles connection management, command execution, and backend-specific error handling while maintaining compatibility with the abstract Store interface defined in AR-012.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: Redis Store Implementation\n18: \n19: The system SHALL provide a Redis-backed Store implementation using `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` that satisfies the Store interface.\n20: \n21: #### Scenario: Redis Ping returns PONG\n22: - **GIVEN** a healthy Redis server at `REDIS_ADDR`\n23: - **AND** a valid `redisStore` instance\n24: - **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called\n25: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL issue `PING` command\n26: - **AND** require string response `PONG`\n27: - **AND** return `nil` error on success\n28: \n29: #### Scenario: Redis Ping fails on connection error\n30: - **GIVEN** an unreachable Redis server\n31: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n32: - **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called\n33: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return a non-nil error indicating connection failure\n34: \n35: #### Scenario: Redis GetSandboxBySessionID returns sandbox\n36: - **GIVEN** a session exists with key `session:abc123` containing valid JSON\n37: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n38: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc123\")` is called\n39: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL issue `GET session:abc123`\n40: - **AND** return the unmarshaled `*types.SandboxInfo`\n41: - **AND** return `nil` error\n42: \n43: #### Scenario: Redis GetSandboxBySessionID returns ErrNotFound for missing key\n44: - **GIVEN** no key `session:abc123` exists in Redis\n45: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n46: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc123\")` is called\n47: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL detect `redis.Nil` error\n48: - **AND** return `ErrNotFound`\n49: \n50: #### Scenario: Redis GetSandboxBySessionID rejects empty session ID\n51: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n52: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n53: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"\")` is called\n54: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n55: - **AND** SHALL NOT query Redis\n56: \n57: #### Scenario: Redis StoreSandbox validates input\n58: - **GIVEN** a nil sandbox pointer\n59: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n60: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, nil)` is called\n61: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sandbox is nil\n62: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Redis commands\n63: \n64: #### Scenario: Redis StoreSandbox validates SessionID\n65: - **GIVEN** a sandbox with `SessionID = \"\"`\n66: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n67: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n68: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n69: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Redis commands\n70: \n71: #### Scenario: Redis StoreSandbox validates ExpiresAt\n72: - **GIVEN** a sandbox with `ExpiresAt = time.Time{}` (zero time)\n73: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n74: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n75: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating expiresAt is zero\n76: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Redis commands\n77: \n78: #### Scenario: Redis StoreSandbox uses atomic pipeline\n79: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`, `ExpiresAt=time.Now().Add(time.Hour)`\n80: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n81: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n82: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute in a pipeline:\n83:   - `SETNX session:sess-1 {json}`\n84:   - `ZADD session:expiry {expires_unix} sess-1`\n85:   - `ZADD session:last_activity {now_unix} sess-1`\n86: - **AND** all commands SHALL succeed\n87: \n88: #### Scenario: Redis StoreSandbox fails if session already exists\n89: - **GIVEN** a session key `session:sess-1` already exists\n90: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n91: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called with same SessionID\n92: - **THEN** `SETNX` SHALL return `false`\n93: - **AND** the implementation SHALL return error indicating session already exists\n94: \n95: #### Scenario: Redis UpdateSandbox requires existing key\n96: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n97: - **AND** key `session:sess-1` does NOT exist\n98: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n99: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n100: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `SET session:sess-1 {json} XX`\n101: - **AND** when result is `false`, return error `key not exists`\n102: \n103: #### Scenario: Redis UpdateSandbox succeeds for existing key\n104: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n105: - **AND** key `session:sess-1` exists\n106: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n107: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n108: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `SET session:sess-1 {json} XX`\n109: - **AND** return `nil` error\n110: - **AND** SHALL NOT modify expiry or activity ZSETs\n111: \n112: #### Scenario: Redis DeleteSandboxBySessionID rejects empty session ID\n113: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n114: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n115: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"\")` is called\n116: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n117: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Redis commands\n118: \n119: #### Scenario: Redis DeleteSandboxBySessionID uses atomic pipeline\n120: - **GIVEN** an existing session with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n121: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n122: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"sess-1\")` is called\n123: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute in a pipeline:\n124:   - `DEL session:sess-1`\n125:   - `ZREM session:expiry sess-1`\n126:   - `ZREM session:last_activity sess-1`\n127: - **AND** return `nil` error\n128: \n129: #### Scenario: Redis ListExpiredSandboxes queries expiry ZSET\n130: - **GIVEN** `before = time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n131: - **AND** `limit = 10`\n132: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n133: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n134: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `ZRANGE session:expiry -inf 1234567890 BYSCORE LIMIT 0 10`\n135: - **AND** for each returned session ID, fetch the full document\n136: - **AND** return slice of `*types.SandboxInfo`\n137: \n138: #### Scenario: Redis ListExpiredSandboxes returns nil for limit <= 0\n139: - **GIVEN** `limit = 0` (or negative)\n140: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n141: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n142: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `nil, nil` without querying Redis\n143: \n144: #### Scenario: Redis ListExpiredSandboxes skips orphaned entries\n145: - **GIVEN** ZSET `session:expiry` contains session ID `orphan-1`\n146: - **AND** key `session:orphan-1` does NOT exist\n147: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n148: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n149: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL skip `orphan-1` in results\n150: - **AND** return only valid sessions\n151: \n152: #### Scenario: Redis ListInactiveSandboxes queries activity ZSET\n153: - **GIVEN** `before = time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n154: - **AND** `limit = 10`\n155: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n156: - **WHEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n157: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `ZRANGE session:last_activity -inf 1234567890 BYSCORE LIMIT 0 10`\n158: - **AND** for each returned session ID, fetch the full document\n159: - **AND** return slice of `*types.SandboxInfo`\n160: \n161: #### Scenario: Redis ListInactiveSandboxes returns nil for limit <= 0\n162: - **GIVEN** `limit = -1` (or zero)\n163: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n164: - **WHEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n165: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `nil, nil` without querying Redis\n166: \n167: #### Scenario: Redis UpdateSessionLastActivity rejects empty session ID\n168: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n169: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n170: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"\", now)` is called\n171: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n172: - **AND** SHALL NOT query Redis\n173: \n174: #### Scenario: Redis UpdateSessionLastActivity verifies existence\n175: - **GIVEN** session ID `unknown-sess`\n176: - **AND** key `session:unknown-sess` does NOT exist\n177: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n178: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"unknown-sess\", now)` is called\n179: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `EXISTS session:unknown-sess`\n180: - **AND** when result is `0`, return `ErrNotFound`\n181: - **AND** SHALL NOT update activity index\n182: \n183: #### Scenario: Redis UpdateSessionLastActivity uses current time for zero\n184: - **GIVEN** an existing session with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n185: - **AND** `at = time.Time{}` (zero time)\n186: - **AND** current time is `time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n187: - **AND** a `redisStore` instance\n188: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"sess-1\", at)` is called\n189: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL use `time.Now()`\n190: - **AND** execute `ZADD session:last_activity 1234567890 sess-1`\n191: \n192: #### Scenario: Redis Close releases connection\n193: - **GIVEN** a `redisStore` instance with active connection\n194: - **WHEN** `Close()` is called\n195: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL call `cli.Close()` on the Redis client\n196: - **AND** return the resulting error (nil on success)\n197: \n198: ---\n199: \n200: ### Requirement: Valkey Store Implementation\n201: \n202: The system SHALL provide a Valkey-backed Store implementation using `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` that satisfies the Store interface.\n203: \n204: #### Scenario: Valkey Ping returns PONG\n205: - **GIVEN** a healthy Valkey server at `VALKEY_ADDR`\n206: - **AND** a valid `valkeyStore` instance\n207: - **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called\n208: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL issue `PING` command via `B().Ping().Build()`\n209: - **AND** require string response `PONG`\n210: - **AND** return `nil` error on success\n211: \n212: #### Scenario: Valkey Ping fails on connection error\n213: - **GIVEN** an unreachable Valkey server\n214: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n215: - **WHEN** `Ping(ctx)` is called\n216: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return a non-nil error indicating connection failure\n217: \n218: #### Scenario: Valkey GetSandboxBySessionID returns sandbox\n219: - **GIVEN** a session exists with key `session:abc123` containing valid JSON\n220: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n221: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc123\")` is called\n222: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL issue `GET session:abc123`\n223: - **AND** return the unmarshaled `*types.SandboxInfo`\n224: - **AND** return `nil` error\n225: \n226: #### Scenario: Valkey GetSandboxBySessionID returns ErrNotFound for missing key\n227: - **GIVEN** no key `session:abc123` exists in Valkey\n228: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n229: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"abc123\")` is called\n230: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL detect `IsValkeyNil` error\n231: - **AND** return `ErrNotFound`\n232: \n233: #### Scenario: Valkey GetSandboxBySessionID rejects empty session ID\n234: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n235: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n236: - **WHEN** `GetSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"\")` is called\n237: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n238: - **AND** SHALL NOT query Valkey\n239: \n240: #### Scenario: Valkey StoreSandbox validates input\n241: - **GIVEN** a nil sandbox pointer\n242: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n243: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, nil)` is called\n244: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sandbox is nil\n245: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Valkey commands\n246: \n247: #### Scenario: Valkey StoreSandbox validates SessionID\n248: - **GIVEN** a sandbox with `SessionID = \"\"`\n249: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n250: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n251: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n252: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Valkey commands\n253: \n254: #### Scenario: Valkey StoreSandbox validates ExpiresAt\n255: - **GIVEN** a sandbox with `ExpiresAt = time.Time{}` (zero time)\n256: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n257: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n258: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating expiresAt is zero\n259: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Valkey commands\n260: \n261: #### Scenario: Valkey StoreSandbox uses DoMulti\n262: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`, `ExpiresAt=time.Now().Add(time.Hour)`\n263: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n264: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n265: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute via `DoMulti`:\n266:   - `SET session:sess-1 {json} NX`\n267:   - `ZADD session:expiry {expires_unix} sess-1`\n268:   - `ZADD session:last_activity {now_unix} sess-1`\n269: - **AND** check first result for \"OK\" indicating success\n270: \n271: #### Scenario: Valkey StoreSandbox fails if session already exists\n272: - **GIVEN** a session key `session:sess-1` already exists\n273: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n274: - **WHEN** `StoreSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called with same SessionID\n275: - **THEN** `SET NX` SHALL NOT return \"OK\"\n276: - **AND** the implementation SHALL return error indicating session already exists\n277: \n278: #### Scenario: Valkey UpdateSandbox requires existing key\n279: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n280: - **AND** key `session:sess-1` does NOT exist\n281: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n282: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n283: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `SET session:sess-1 {json} XX`\n284: - **AND** when result is not \"OK\", return error `key not exists`\n285: \n286: #### Scenario: Valkey UpdateSandbox succeeds for existing key\n287: - **GIVEN** a valid sandbox with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n288: - **AND** key `session:sess-1` exists\n289: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n290: - **WHEN** `UpdateSandbox(ctx, sandbox)` is called\n291: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `SET session:sess-1 {json} XX`\n292: - **AND** return `nil` error\n293: - **AND** SHALL NOT modify expiry or activity ZSETs\n294: \n295: #### Scenario: Valkey DeleteSandboxBySessionID rejects empty session ID\n296: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n297: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n298: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"\")` is called\n299: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n300: - **AND** SHALL NOT execute any Valkey commands\n301: \n302: #### Scenario: Valkey DeleteSandboxBySessionID uses DoMulti\n303: - **GIVEN** an existing session with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n304: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n305: - **WHEN** `DeleteSandboxBySessionID(ctx, \"sess-1\")` is called\n306: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute via `DoMulti`:\n307:   - `DEL session:sess-1`\n308:   - `ZREM session:expiry sess-1`\n309:   - `ZREM session:last_activity sess-1`\n310: - **AND** return `nil` error\n311: \n312: #### Scenario: Valkey ListExpiredSandboxes queries expiry ZSET\n313: - **GIVEN** `before = time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n314: - **AND** `limit = 10`\n315: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n316: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n317: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `ZRANGEBYSCORE session:expiry -inf 1234567890 LIMIT 0 10`\n318: - **AND** for each returned session ID, fetch the full document\n319: - **AND** return slice of `*types.SandboxInfo`\n320: \n321: #### Scenario: Valkey ListExpiredSandboxes returns nil for limit <= 0\n322: - **GIVEN** `limit = 0` (or negative)\n323: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n324: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n325: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `nil, nil` without querying Valkey\n326: \n327: #### Scenario: Valkey ListExpiredSandboxes skips orphaned entries\n328: - **GIVEN** ZSET `session:expiry` contains session ID `orphan-1`\n329: - **AND** key `session:orphan-1` does NOT exist (MGET returns empty string)\n330: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n331: - **WHEN** `ListExpiredSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n332: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL skip empty results\n333: - **AND** return only valid sessions\n334: \n335: #### Scenario: Valkey ListInactiveSandboxes queries activity ZSET\n336: - **GIVEN** `before = time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n337: - **AND** `limit = 10`\n338: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n339: - **WHEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n340: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `ZRANGEBYSCORE session:last_activity -inf 1234567890 LIMIT 0 10`\n341: - **AND** for each returned session ID, fetch the full document\n342: - **AND** return slice of `*types.SandboxInfo`\n343: \n344: #### Scenario: Valkey ListInactiveSandboxes returns nil for limit <= 0\n345: - **GIVEN** `limit = -1` (or zero)\n346: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n347: - **WHEN** `ListInactiveSandboxes(ctx, before, limit)` is called\n348: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return `nil, nil` without querying Valkey\n349: \n350: #### Scenario: Valkey UpdateSessionLastActivity rejects empty session ID\n351: - **GIVEN** an empty session ID `\"\"`\n352: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n353: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"\", now)` is called\n354: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL return an error indicating sessionID is empty\n355: - **AND** SHALL NOT query Valkey\n356: \n357: #### Scenario: Valkey UpdateSessionLastActivity verifies existence\n358: - **GIVEN** session ID `unknown-sess`\n359: - **AND** key `session:unknown-sess` does NOT exist\n360: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n361: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"unknown-sess\", now)` is called\n362: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL execute `EXISTS session:unknown-sess`\n363: - **AND** when result is `0`, return `ErrNotFound`\n364: - **AND** SHALL NOT update activity index\n365: \n366: #### Scenario: Valkey UpdateSessionLastActivity uses current time for zero\n367: - **GIVEN** an existing session with `SessionID=\"sess-1\"`\n368: - **AND** `at = time.Time{}` (zero time)\n369: - **AND** current time is `time.Unix(1234567890, 0)`\n370: - **AND** a `valkeyStore` instance\n371: - **WHEN** `UpdateSessionLastActivity(ctx, \"sess-1\", at)` is called\n372: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL use `time.Now()`\n373: - **AND** execute `ZADD session:last_activity 1234567890 sess-1`\n374: \n375: #### Scenario: Valkey Close releases connection\n376: - **GIVEN** a `valkeyStore` instance with active connection\n377: - **WHEN** `Close()` is called\n378: - **THEN** the implementation SHALL call `cli.Close()` on the Valkey client\n379: - **AND** return `nil`\n380: \n381: ---\n382: \n383: ### Requirement: Redis Environment Configuration\n384: \n385: The system SHALL require `REDIS_ADDR`. The system SHALL require non-empty `REDIS_PASSWORD` unless `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` is set case-insensitively to `false`.\n386: \n387: #### Scenario: Redis address is required\n388: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR` environment variable is not set\n389: - **WHEN** `newRedisStore()` is called\n390: - **THEN** the function SHALL return an error indicating `REDIS_ADDR is required`\n391: - **AND** SHALL NOT create a Redis client\n392: \n393: #### Scenario: Redis password required by default\n394: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR=localhost:6379`\n395: - **AND** `REDIS_PASSWORD` is empty\n396: - **AND** `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` is unset\n397: - **WHEN** `newRedisStore()` is called\n398: - **THEN** the function SHALL return an error indicating `REDIS_PASSWORD is required`\n399: \n400: #### Scenario: Redis password can be disabled\n401: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_ADDR=localhost:6379`\n402: - **AND** `REDIS_PASSWORD` is empty\n403: - **AND** `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`\n404: - **WHEN** `newRedisStore()` is called\n405: - **THEN** the function SHALL succeed\n406: - **AND** create a Redis client with empty password\n407: \n408: #### Scenario: Redis password requirement is case-insensitive\n409: - **GIVEN** `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=FALSE` (uppercase)\n410: - **WHEN** parsing the option\n411: - **THEN** the system SHALL treat it as disabled\n412: \n413: ---\n414: \n415: ### Requirement: Valkey Environment Configuration\n416: \n417: The system SHALL require `VALKEY_ADDR` (comma-separated addresses). The system SHALL require non-empty `VALKEY_PASSWORD` unless `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`. The system SHALL set `DisableCache` true when `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` parses as true; SHALL set `ForceSingleClient` true when `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` parses as true.\n418: \n419: #### Scenario: Valkey address is required\n420: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_ADDR` environment variable is not set\n421: - **WHEN** `newValkeyStore()` is called\n422: - **THEN** the function SHALL return an error indicating `VALKEY_ADDR is required`\n423: - **AND** SHALL NOT create a Valkey client\n424: \n425: #### Scenario: Valkey parses comma-separated addresses\n426: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_ADDR=valkey1:6379,valkey2:6379,valkey3:6379`\n427: - **WHEN** `makeValkeyOptions()` is called\n428: - **THEN** `InitAddress` SHALL be `[\"valkey1:6379\", \"valkey2:6379\", \"valkey3:6379\"]`\n429: \n430: #### Scenario: Valkey password required by default\n431: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_ADDR=localhost:6379`\n432: - **AND** `VALKEY_PASSWORD` is empty\n433: - **AND** `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` is unset\n434: - **WHEN** `newValkeyStore()` is called\n435: - **THEN** the function SHALL return an error indicating `VALKEY_PASSWORD is required`\n436: \n437: #### Scenario: Valkey password can be disabled\n438: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_ADDR=localhost:6379`\n439: - **AND** `VALKEY_PASSWORD` is empty\n440: - **AND** `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED=false`\n441: - **WHEN** `newValkeyStore()` is called\n442: - **THEN** the function SHALL succeed\n443: - **AND** create a Valkey client without password\n444: \n445: #### Scenario: Valkey DisableCache when VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE=true\n446: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE=true`\n447: - **WHEN** `makeValkeyOptions()` is called\n448: - **THEN** `DisableCache` SHALL be `true`\n449: \n450: #### Scenario: Valkey ForceSingleClient when VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE=true\n451: - **GIVEN** `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE=true`\n452: - **WHEN** `makeValkeyOptions()` is called\n453: - **THEN** `ForceSingleClient` SHALL be `true`\n454: \n455: ---\n456: \n457: ## Changes to Base Specification\n458: \n459: No modifications to existing interfaces. This AR implements the Store interface defined in AR-012 for Redis and Valkey backends.\n460: \n461: ---\n462: \n463: ## New Interfaces\n464: \n465: ### Redis Store Internal Types\n466: \n467: ```go\n468: // redisOptions holds Redis connection configuration.\n469: type redisOptions struct {\n470:     Addr     string\n471:     Password string\n472: }\n473: ```\n474: \n475: ### Valkey Store Internal Types\n476: \n477: ```go\n478: // valkeyOptions holds Valkey connection configuration.\n479: type valkeyOptions struct {\n480:     InitAddress       []string\n481:     Password          string\n482:     DisableCache      bool\n483:     ForceSingleClient bool\n484: }\n485: ```\n486: \n487: ---\n488: \n489: ## Modified Interfaces\n490: \n491: None. This AR implements existing interfaces without modification.\n492: \n493: ---\n494: \n495: ## Behavioral Changes\n496: \n497: | Behavior | Before | After |\n498: |----------|--------|-------|\n499: | Redis Store | Interface only | Full Redis implementation in `redis.go` |\n500: | Valkey Store | Interface only | Full Valkey implementation in `valkey.go` |\n501: | Connection management | None | Redis client with pooling via go-redis/v9 |\n502: | Connection management | None | Valkey client via valkey-go |\n503: | Command execution | None | Full Redis command support via Pipeline |\n504: | Command execution | None | Full Valkey command support via DoMulti |\n505: \n506: ---\n507: \n508: ## Dependencies\n509: \n510: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n511: |------------|---------|---------|\n512: | `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` | v9.x | Redis client for Go |\n513: | `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` | Latest | Valkey client for Go |\n514: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/store` | Local | Store interface definition |\n515: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | Local | SandboxInfo type definition |\n516: \n517: ---\n518: \n519: ## File Index\n520: \n521: | Path | Purpose |\n522: |------|---------|\n523: | `pkg/store/redis.go` | Redis Store implementation |\n524: | `pkg/store/valkey.go` | Valkey Store implementation |\n525: | `pkg/store/singleton.go` | Provider selection and initialization |\n526: \n527: ---\n528: \n529: ## Constants\n530: \n531: | Constant | Value | Description |\n532: |----------|-------|-------------|\n533: | `sessionPrefix` | `\"session:\"` | Key prefix for session data |\n534: | `expiryIndexKey` | `\"session:expiry\"` | ZSET key for expiry tracking |\n535: | `lastActivityIndexKey` | `\"session:last_activity\"` | ZSET key for activity tracking |\n536: \n537: ---\n538: \n539: ## Environment Variables\n540: \n541: ### Redis Configuration\n542: \n543: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n544: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n545: | `REDIS_ADDR` | Yes | - | Redis server address (host:port) |\n546: | `REDIS_PASSWORD` | Yes* | - | Redis authentication password |\n547: | `REDIS_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Set to `false` to allow empty password |\n548: \n549: ### Valkey Configuration\n550: \n551: | Variable | Required | Default | Description |\n552: |----------|----------|---------|-------------|\n553: | `VALKEY_ADDR` | Yes | - | Comma-separated Valkey addresses |\n554: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD` | Yes* | - | Valkey authentication password |\n555: | `VALKEY_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` | No | `true` | Set to `false` to allow empty password |\n556: | `VALKEY_DISABLE_CACHE` | No | `false` | Set to `true` to disable client cache |\n557: | `VALKEY_FORCE_SINGLE` | No | `false` | Set to `true` for single client mode |\n558: \n559: *Required unless the corresponding `_PASSWORD_REQUIRED` is set to `false`\n560: \n561: ---\n562: \n563: ## API Endpoints Summary\n564: \n565: This AR provides library functionality; no HTTP endpoints are directly exposed.\n566: \n567: ---\n568: \n569: ## Migration Notes\n570: \n571: - **New dependencies**: Add `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` and `github.com/valkey-io/valkey-go` to go.mod\n572: - **Environment setup**: Configure `REDIS_ADDR` or `VALKEY_ADDR` before deployment\n573: - **File naming**: Implementation files are `redis.go` and `valkey.go` (not `store_redis.go`/`store_valkey.go`)\n574: \n575: ---\n576: \n577: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n578: \n579: 1. **Redis Implementation Completeness**: All Store interface methods implemented for Redis\n580: 2. **Valkey Implementation Completeness**: All Store interface methods implemented for Valkey\n581: 3. **Error Handling**: Redis/Valkey errors properly translated to store errors (ErrNotFound)\n582: 4. **Atomicity**: Pipeline operations ensure atomic writes for StoreSandbox and Delete\n583: 5. **Index Management**: ZSET indexes maintained correctly for both backends\n584: 6. **Connection Management**: Proper client lifecycle handling for both Redis and Valkey\n585: 7. **Environment Validation**: Required environment variables validated at initialization\n586: 8. **Test Coverage**: Unit and integration tests pass for both implementations\n\n(End of file - total 586 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-013: Redis 存储实现 (Redis Storage Implementation) - Delta Specification\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-013  \n**Module:** `pkg/store`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Base Spec:** [AR-012: 会话存储接口定义](../AR-012/delta-spec.md)\n\nThe Redis Storage Implementation provides concrete implementations of the Store interface using Redis and Valkey as backends. It handles connection management, command execution, and backend-specific error handling while maintaining compatibility with the abstract Store interface defined in AR-012.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: Redis Store Implementation\n\nThe system SHALL provide a Redis-backed Store implementation using `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` that satisfies the Store interface.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-013/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775874957833,"end":1775874957854}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775874957859,"sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","part":{"id":"prt_d7a655bff001AwU5WNKx0DLUvS","messageID":"msg_d7a653c96001g9I7cTwtvtLvJr","sessionID":"ses_2859af2f6ffe6Dgxn0a1FnVUa2","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/picod/types.go"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/picod/types.go</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: /*\n2: Copyright 2026 The Volcano Authors.\n3: \n4: Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n5: you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n6: You may obtain a copy of the License at\n7: \n8:     http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n9: \n10: Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n11: distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n12: WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n13: See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n14: limitations under the License.\n15: */\n16: \n17: package picod\n18: \n19: import (\n20: \t\"context\"\n21: \t\"fmt\"\n22: \t\"strings\"\n23: \t\"time\"\n24: \n25: \t\"github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types\"\n26: )\n27: \n28: // ExecutionID uniquely identifies a command execution.\n29: type ExecutionID string\n30: \n31: // ExecutionState represents the state of command execution.\n32: type ExecutionState string\n33: \n34: const (\n35: \t// StatePending indicates the execution is queued\n36: \tStatePending ExecutionState = \"pending\"\n37: \n38: \t// StateRunning indicates the execution is in progress\n39: \tStateRunning ExecutionState = \"running\"\n40: \n41: \t// StateCompleted indicates the execution completed successfully\n42: \tStateCompleted ExecutionState = \"completed\"\n43: \n44: \t// StateFailed indicates the execution failed\n45: \tStateFailed ExecutionState = \"failed\"\n46: \n47: \t// StateCancelled indicates the execution was cancelled\n48: \tStateCancelled ExecutionState = \"cancelled\"\n49: )\n50: \n51: // IsTerminal returns true if the state is terminal (completed, failed, or cancelled).\n52: func (s ExecutionState) IsTerminal() bool {\n53: \treturn s == StateCompleted || s == StateFailed || s == StateCancelled\n54: }\n55: \n56: // String returns the string representation of the state.\n57: func (s ExecutionState) String() string {\n58: \treturn string(s)\n59: }\n60: \n61: // ExecutionRequest contains parameters for command execution.\n62: type ExecutionRequest struct {\n63: \t// Command is the command to execute (required)\n64: \tCommand string `json:\"command\"`\n65: \n66: \t// Args are the command arguments\n67: \tArgs []string `json:\"args,omitempty\"`\n68: \n69: \t// WorkingDir is the working directory for execution (default: sandbox default)\n70: \tWorkingDir string `json:\"workingDir,omitempty\"`\n71: \n72: \t// Environment defines environment variables (merged with sandbox defaults)\n73: \tEnvironment map[string]string `json:\"environment,omitempty\"`\n74: \n75: \t// Timeout is the maximum execution time (default: 30s)\n76: \tTimeout time.Duration `json:\"timeout,omitempty\"`\n77: \n78: \t// ResourceLimits defines resource constraints for execution\n79: \tResourceLimits ResourceConstraints `json:\"resourceLimits,omitempty\"`\n80: \n81: \t// SessionID identifies the target sandbox (required)\n82: \tSessionID string `json:\"sessionId\"`\n83: }\n84: \n85: // Validate validates the execution request.\n86: func (r *ExecutionRequest) Validate() error {\n87: \tif strings.TrimSpace(r.Command) == \"\" {\n88: \t\treturn ErrInvalidCommand\n89: \t}\n90: \tif strings.Contains(r.Command, \"..\") || strings.Contains(r.Command, \"//\") {\n91: \t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: command contains invalid characters\", ErrInvalidCommand)\n92: \t}\n93: \tif r.SessionID == \"\" {\n94: \t\treturn ErrInvalidSessionID\n95: \t}\n96: \tif r.WorkingDir != \"\" && !isAllowedWorkingDir(r.WorkingDir) {\n97: \t\treturn ErrInvalidWorkingDir\n98: \t}\n99: \tfor name := range r.Environment {\n100: \t\tif !isValidEnvVarName(name) {\n101: \t\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: invalid environment variable name: %s\", ErrInvalidRequest, name)\n102: \t\t}\n103: \t}\n104: \treturn nil\n105: }\n106: \n107: // ExecutionResult contains the result of a command execution.\n108: type ExecutionResult struct {\n109: \t// ID is the unique execution identifier\n110: \tID ExecutionID `json:\"id\"`\n111: \n112: \t// Status contains the execution status details\n113: \tStatus ExecutionStatus `json:\"status\"`\n114: \n115: \t// ExitCode is the command exit code (0 for success)\n116: \tExitCode int `json:\"exitCode\"`\n117: \n118: \t// Stdout contains the captured standard output\n119: \tStdout []byte `json:\"stdout,omitempty\"`\n120: \n121: \t// Stderr contains the captured standard error\n122: \tStderr []byte `json:\"stderr,omitempty\"`\n123: \n124: \t// StartedAt is when execution started\n125: \tStartedAt time.Time `json:\"startedAt\"`\n126: \n127: \t// FinishedAt is when execution completed\n128: \tFinishedAt time.Time `json:\"finishedAt\"`\n129: \n130: \t// Error contains error details if execution failed\n131: \tError *ExecutionError `json:\"error,omitempty\"`\n132: \n133: \t// Truncated indicates if output was truncated due to size limits\n134: \tTruncated bool `json:\"truncated,omitempty\"`\n135: }\n136: \n137: // ExecutionError contains detailed error information.\n138: type ExecutionError struct {\n139: \t// Code is the machine-readable error code\n140: \tCode string `json:\"code\"`\n141: \n142: \t// Message is the human-readable error message\n143: \tMessage string `json:\"message\"`\n144: \n145: \t// Details contains additional error context\n146: \tDetails map[string]interface{} `json:\"details,omitempty\"`\n147: }\n148: \n149: // ExecutionStatus represents the current state of an execution.\n150: type ExecutionStatus struct {\n151: \t// ID is the unique execution identifier\n152: \tID ExecutionID `json:\"id\"`\n153: \n154: \t// State is the current execution state\n155: \tState ExecutionState `json:\"state\"`\n156: \n157: \t// StartedAt is when execution started (nil if not started)\n158: \tStartedAt *time.Time `json:\"startedAt,omitempty\"`\n159: \n160: \t// FinishedAt is when execution completed (nil if not finished)\n161: \tFinishedAt *time.Time `json:\"finishedAt,omitempty\"`\n162: \n163: \t// ExitCode is the command exit code (nil if not finished)\n164: \tExitCode *int `json:\"exitCode,omitempty\"`\n165: \n166: \t// OutputRef references stored output (for large outputs)\n167: \tOutputRef string `json:\"outputRef,omitempty\"`\n168: \n169: \t// SessionID is the target sandbox session ID\n170: \tSessionID string `json:\"sessionId\"`\n171: }\n172: \n173: // ResourceConstraints defines resource limits for execution.\n174: type ResourceConstraints struct {\n175: \t// MaxMemory is the maximum memory in bytes (0 = unlimited)\n176: \tMaxMemory int64 `json:\"maxMemory,omitempty\"`\n177: \n178: \t// MaxCPU is the maximum CPU percentage (0-100, 0 = unlimited)\n179: \tMaxCPU float64 `json:\"maxCpu,omitempty\"`\n180: \n181: \t// MaxIOBytes is the maximum IO bandwidth in bytes per second (0 = unlimited)\n182: \tMaxIOBytes int64 `json:\"maxIoBytes,omitempty\"`\n183: \n184: \t// MaxFiles is the maximum number of open file descriptors (0 = unlimited)\n185: \tMaxFiles int `json:\"maxFiles,omitempty\"`\n186: }\n187: \n188: // IsEmpty returns true if no constraints are set.\n189: func (r ResourceConstraints) IsEmpty() bool {\n190: \treturn r.MaxMemory == 0 && r.MaxCPU == 0 && r.MaxIOBytes == 0 && r.MaxFiles == 0\n191: }\n192: \n193: // Validate validates resource constraints.\n194: func (r ResourceConstraints) Validate() error {\n195: \tif r.MaxMemory < 0 {\n196: \t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: maxMemory cannot be negative\", ErrInvalidRequest)\n197: \t}\n198: \tif r.MaxCPU < 0 || r.MaxCPU > 100 {\n199: \t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: maxCpu must be between 0 and 100\", ErrInvalidRequest)\n200: \t}\n201: \tif r.MaxIOBytes < 0 {\n202: \t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: maxIoBytes cannot be negative\", ErrInvalidRequest)\n203: \t}\n204: \tif r.MaxFiles < 0 {\n205: \t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"%w: maxFiles cannot be negative\", ErrInvalidRequest)\n206: \t}\n207: \treturn nil\n208: }\n209: \n210: // OutputChunk represents a piece of output from a command.\n211: type OutputChunk struct {\n212: \t// Data is the output data\n213: \tData []byte `json:\"data\"`\n214: \n215: \t// Type indicates the output source\n216: \tType OutputType `json:\"type\"`\n217: \n218: \t// Timestamp is when the output was captured\n219: \tTimestamp time.Time `json:\"timestamp\"`\n220: }\n221: \n222: // OutputType indicates the source of output.\n223: type OutputType string\n224: \n225: const (\n226: \t// Stdout indicates standard output\n227: \tStdout OutputType = \"stdout\"\n228: \n229: \t// Stderr indicates standard error\n230: \tStderr OutputType = \"stderr\"\n231: )\n232: \n233: // String returns the string representation of the output type.\n234: func (o OutputType) String() string {\n235: \treturn string(o)\n236: }\n237: \n238: // CommandExecutor defines the interface for executing commands in sandboxes.\n239: type CommandExecutor interface {\n240: \t// Execute runs a command synchronously and returns the result.\n241: \t// Blocks until execution completes, times out, or is cancelled.\n242: \tExecute(ctx context.Context, req ExecutionRequest) (*ExecutionResult, error)\n243: \n244: \t// ExecuteAsync runs a command asynchronously and returns an execution ID.\n245: \t// Returns immediately; use GetStatus to poll for completion.\n246: \tExecuteAsync(ctx context.Context, req ExecutionRequest) (ExecutionID, error)\n247: \n248: \t// GetStatus retrieves the current status of an execution.\n249: \t// Returns ErrExecutionNotFound if the execution does not exist.\n250: \tGetStatus(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (*ExecutionStatus, error)\n251: \n252: \t// Cancel stops a running execution.\n253: \t// Returns ErrExecutionAlreadyComplete if execution is in terminal state.\n254: \tCancel(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) error\n255: \n256: \t// StreamOutput returns a channel for streaming output from an execution.\n257: \t// Channel is closed when execution completes or context is cancelled.\n258: \tStreamOutput(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (<-chan OutputChunk, error)\n259: }\n260: \n261: // ExecutionStore defines the interface for execution status persistence.\n262: type ExecutionStore interface {\n263: \t// CreateStatus creates a new execution status record.\n264: \tCreateStatus(ctx context.Context, status *ExecutionStatus) error\n265: \n266: \t// GetStatus retrieves execution status by ID.\n267: \t// Returns ErrExecutionNotFound if not found.\n268: \tGetStatus(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (*ExecutionStatus, error)\n269: \n270: \t// UpdateStatus updates execution status.\n271: \tUpdateStatus(ctx context.Context, status *ExecutionStatus) error\n272: \n273: \t// UpdateStatusWithTransition updates status with state transition validation.\n274: \t// Only allows valid state transitions.\n275: \tUpdateStatusWithTransition(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID, from, to ExecutionState, updateFn func(*ExecutionStatus)) error\n276: \n277: \t// DeleteStatus removes an execution status record.\n278: \tDeleteStatus(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) error\n279: \n280: \t// ListExecutions lists executions filtered by state and session.\n281: \tListExecutions(ctx context.Context, filter ExecutionFilter) ([]*ExecutionStatus, error)\n282: \n283: \t// StoreOutput stores execution output for later retrieval.\n284: \tStoreOutput(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID, stdout, stderr []byte) error\n285: \n286: \t// GetOutput retrieves stored execution output.\n287: \tGetOutput(ctx context.Context, id ExecutionID) (stdout, stderr []byte, err error)\n288: }\n289: \n290: // ExecutionFilter defines filters for listing executions.\n291: type ExecutionFilter struct {\n292: \t// SessionID filters by session\n293: \tSessionID string\n294: \n295: \t// State filters by execution state\n296: \tState ExecutionState\n297: \n298: \t// Limit limits the number of results\n299: \tLimit int\n300: }\n301: \n302: // SandboxResolver resolves session IDs to sandbox information.\n303: type SandboxResolver interface {\n304: \t// Resolve returns sandbox info for a session ID.\n305: \t// Returns ErrSandboxUnavailable if session doesn't exist.\n306: \tResolve(ctx context.Context, sessionID string) (*types.SandboxInfo, error)\n307: }\n308: \n309: // SandboxRunner executes commands in a sandbox.\n310: type SandboxRunner interface {\n311: \t// Run executes a command synchronously.\n312: \tRun(ctx context.Context, sandbox *types.SandboxInfo, req ExecutionRequest) (*ExecutionResult, error)\n313: \n314: \t// Start begins async command execution.\n315: \tStart(ctx context.Context, sandbox *types.SandboxInfo, req ExecutionRequest, id ExecutionID) error\n316: \n317: \t// Cancel stops a running command.\n318: \tCancel(ctx context.Context, sandbox *types.SandboxInfo, id ExecutionID) error\n319: }\n320: \n321: // QueuedExecution represents an execution in the queue.\n322: type QueuedExecution struct {\n323: \tID         ExecutionID\n324: \tRequest    ExecutionRequest\n325: \tEnqueuedAt time.Time\n326: }\n327: \n328: // ExecutionQueue manages the async execution queue.\n329: type ExecutionQueue interface {\n330: \t// Enqueue adds an execution request to the queue.\n331: \t// Returns the assigned execution ID.\n332: \tEnqueue(req ExecutionRequest) (ExecutionID, error)\n333: \n334: \t// Dequeue retrieves the next pending execution.\n335: \t// Blocks until an execution is available or context is cancelled.\n336: \tDequeue(ctx context.Context) (*QueuedExecution, error)\n337: \n338: \t// GetPosition returns the queue position for an execution.\n339: \tGetPosition(id ExecutionID) (int, error)\n340: \n341: \t// Remove removes an execution from the queue.\n342: \tRemove(id ExecutionID) error\n343: \n344: \t// Size returns the current queue size.\n345: \tSize() int\n346: }\n\n(End of file - total 346 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"/*\nCopyright 2026 The Volcano Authors.\n\nLicensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\nyou may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\nYou may obtain a copy of the License at\n\n    http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n\nUnless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\ndistributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\nWITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\nSee the License for the specific language governing permissions and\nlimitations under the License.\n*/\n\npackage picod\n\nimport (\n\t\"context\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/picod/types.go","time":{"start":1775874957835,"end":1775874957857}}}}
